Worst thing in the world:

I don't like going to the bathroom when people can hear me and I have 5 roommates and the bathroom isn't sound proof.

So my father calls this morning and asks, 'hey, do you want to go to a play tonight?'  I respond with, 'what play?'  'The Lion King on Broadway'

Holy crap, of course I want to go see it.  Not that it's the best of the Broadway in Portland series, but it's pretty high up there and the last one that'll be here while I'm actually still living in Vancouver.  I'm so stoaked!
It is now 1:20 AM and I have a breathing apparatus in my mouth.

So I'm drawing all these cartoons for the openning of Fatti Island but my scanner is being an asshole and just locking up the computer.  No big deal, I think, I'll just take pictures of them and then upload them that way.  But no, my digital camera has to choose today of all days to go and break.  So now I not only don't have a way to do the openning, but I don't have a digital camera anymore either.  Somebody I can kill needs to come over to visit and bring a nice big butcher knife with them.

Daytime television sucks and I hate stupid people.

Direct quote from a guy on Maury: "I'm not the father.  I only had sex with her a couple of times, and one of those times, I used a condom."

WTF.

I think the average intelligence of the world must be lowering, because smart people use protection and stupid people don't.

Look at your LJ "interests" list. If you have less than 50 interests, pick every fifth one. If you have between fifty and seventy-five interests, pick every seventh one. If you have over seventy-five interests, pick every tenth one. If you have fewer than ten, pick all of 'em. List them on your LJ, and tell everyone exactly what it is about these things that interests you so much.

I only cheated to make it a more entertaining post.

abe- Because he's a really great penis...er, president.

classic rock- I grew up on this stuff.  How could I not like it?  Even if I didn't grow up on it, how could I not?  And what's wrong with my "R" key?

first kisses- Duh.  The first kiss with someone new is always a rush.  And they often make good stories later.  So, how could I not love them?

intelligence-Stupid people bug the crap out of me.  Get some freakin brains!

kissing left/right- This is one of my unique livejournal intrests.  Meaning, nobody else has it listed.  And it's really an interesting conversation starter: When initiating a kiss, do you tilt your head to the left or the right?

musicals- Only the greatest things ever!  They combine the greatness of instrumental music, vocal music, and drama all into one great fantastic product.  They require a great quantity of people with great quantites of skill to pull off so when they come out good, you know that the program must really rock.  Plus, most of my greatest memories while playing trumpet are in the musical pits.  Frktn!  Now, if I could only figure out what "tacet" means...

percy- Just for the record, I'm really upset that I passed 'orgasms'  Percy is the lawn flamingo that me and Emma liberated the summer before our junior year.  He's named after Sir Percy in The Scarlet Pimpernel.  He has a crack in his neck, but wears a Harry Potter bandaid.

rocko's modern life- Seriously, this show was the shiznit.  I wish I had it on DVD.  Or, for that matter, that they made it on DVD.

sexuality theories- Nature vs. Nurture?  Again, just something fun to discuss and study.  Why do some people like boys while others like girls?  Why does it matter at all?  I mean, barely anybody finds people sexually attractive only if they have red hair, so why should they only find them attractive if they have a penis?  How much of it is simply society's implications playing out?  I find it all incredably intriging.

stick pens- The pens that I bought for college were labeled as "stick pens" and I just thought it was really funny.  I mean, almost all pens are shaped like sticks, so why do they feel the need to label them as stick pens?  I don't really understand, but it's hilarious.

thunder storms-  They're amazing.

wrestling in public- It's fun and people look at you funny.  And, the best part of all, you get to touch people.  I'm a touch whore.  I really am.

Kim brought up the other day something about mindless middle school crushes and how it should still be like when you like someone and your friends make fun of you for it but then you make fun of them for who they like and it changes every week and none of it really matters anyway.

And I thought, hey, I never did that.  That sounds like fun!  But, alas, I was not that type of middle schooler.  I liked two people when I was at Pacific.  And I still like them both today.  Despite the fact that I've barely talked to one of them since.  And that the other is completely unreasonable.  Whatever.  They both come way closer to perfect than anyone who's actually been around.  Well...yeah.  Okay.  Yes.  Than anyone.  Which is stupid because I was 13.  What the hell?  How could I have known so much when I knew so little?  When I was stupid enough to let him get away.  But hey, I was still that stupid at 18, so who can blame it on age anyway?

Kim Smite.

I just...I don't know.  I'm leaving and I thought I was done and it's lame because other people have actual things and this is just me thinking of things that aren't actual, you know.  and what the fuck.  I'll just stop talking now before I think any lower of myself for making this post at all.

Excerpted from a conversation, plus some.

Went outside to bring the garbage can in.  It hit me halfway down my driveway.  I stopped to consider for a moment and pulled my hoodie off.  It's the kind of day that's so perfectly end-of-August it's hard to believe it's real.  It's warm, but not too warm.  You can wear shorts if you want to, but you don't have to.  Blue skies with accompaning clouds.  Everything seems fresh from the rain yesterday and there's a scent and electricity in the air of new beginnings.  Impending newness on the horizon.  (The weather knows this town too well as public schools begin in exactly a week.)

God, it's beautiful.
I heart sudden downpours.  That definitely qualified as makeout rain, and yet, I was running in it alone.  Where were you?

On the topic of the "voting" that we did today.

Mr. Nowacki told 6th period the results from his previous 3 periods and although the issues were overwhelmingly democraticly voted upon, the front side had a 58% Bush lead.  Incredably upsetting, and I'm not saying this because I want Kerry to win (although I do).  This means that a large number of people don't know where the candidates stand on the issues.  And at this age many people are still in tune with their parents on political views.  Notice the many, not all or even most.  So, this now means that many people's parents in the area are going to go out and vote uninformed.  I'm a strong believer of voting on the issues, not the party, and, from the looks of at least the psychology faction of egreen, people around here don't.

Now I'm depressed.

I was going to censor this so certain people couldn't read it, but i decided not to because it's my fucking journal and i'm protected by the first amendment.

I strongly feel that what the section leaders did tonight- the before practice stuff, the sectional lectures, and the "sl's in the middle", the whole nine yards- was extraordinarily uncalled for and inappropriate.  and remember, i've been a section leader, i understand how difficult it is to encourage people while keeping their respect, but this was way out of line.  the entire thing was designed to seperate the sl's from the rest of the band as if they're goD's gift to the EMB while the rest of us are the scum of the earth and worth no more than the crud they scrap off the bottom of their shoes.  Bad move guys, this is not the way effective leaders work.  Effective leaders are well liked.

There are two ways that we, as a band, can have fun during a marching season.  The first is by making the decision of going for that sweepstakes trophy everytime and everybody works hard and it's a blast being hardcore.  The fun comes from what you get back and the feeling when you hit the last big halt at the championship performance.  The other way to have fun is to accept a slightly lower slot on the rankings and just have a blast learning and performing the show.  We enjoy rehersals because we get to laugh and enjoy the company of those around us and we can still enjoy competing because we would still have the potetial to be top 5 and that's plenty of excitment.  The main fun here comes from remembering all the great times you had with all the new friends you;ve made during rehersal.  Both ways are awesomely fun.  Both ways are acceptable to me.  The fact is, I thought we had already choosen the second one to let the band as a program take a breather for a few years after hardcoreness.  I guess we're not allowed to.

And this one has been bugging me all seasion but, yes, even more so now that we cant see yardlines all the time.  When you're marching, you dress the form.  when you're at dress set, you dress the form.  and when he says to find your dot, you find you're fucking dot!  if you look far down the yardlines you can see them and people saying, "we can't dress behind us" is just bullshit because we're not talking about dressing, we're talking about when we have time to stop and set the form correctly.  STOP BEING A DUMBASS!
and the person that last one was emphasized on will know if they read it.

I go out on the field and i march well and i play well.  that's my job.  and i'm getting sick of people giving me crap.  and i'm sick of people giving the band crap.  this is neither of the ways to have fun.  this is the way to get a 40% return rate for next year's marching program.

I think the whole concept of being "homesick" when you go other places for extended periods of time (i.e. camp, college) is all backwards.  I find myself being campsick when I get home.  With few exceptions, you arrive at camp knowing no one.  Human nature is to want to be close to people and have people to care about.  So when you arrive at camp the people you sit next to, room with, and other various nice people end up becoming quick and very important friends.  And sharing something so passionate as music with them makes it all the deeper.  And so by the end of the week you're in love with around 15 or so people.  Then on the last day, the parents show up and everyone splits of to them with no regards to the people they've been living on top of for the past week.  The final concert is performed and you put your instrument away and just leave.  Just walk away.  Zero closure.

Coming soon: music camp quotes!!  Good, sometimes clean fun for the musical and nonmusical alike!
